\begin_layout Standard
We identified chemical synapses in our images by the existence of presynaptic
 vesicles and postsynaptic densities.
 All chemical synapses involving integrator neurons contained small vesicles,
 suggesting the presence of conventional rather than peptidergic neurotransmitte
rs.
 Dense core vesicles were found at other synapses in the same region.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We found one example of an ipsilaterally-projecting integrator neuron that
 made two synapses onto another ipsilaterally-projecting integrator neuron.
 The same source neuron also synapsed onto two contralaterally-projecting
 integrator neurons.
 This provides the first evidence that integrator neurons make synapses
 onto each other.
 The existence of recurrent synapses between integrator neurons has long
 been hypothesized by many computational models of the neural integrator.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Neural circuits transform activity and produce activity that is either sent
 to higher brain areas or to muscles to elicit behavior.
 A very simplistic example of this idea is that of the reflex arc, where
 sensory information is relayed to motor neurons in the spinal chord, in
 order to elicit a reflex.
 More complex behaviors, transform the incoming activity to produce a different/
unique output.
 This transformation presumably involves the integration of signals form
 multiple neurons, to produce a suitable output.
 For example a 5 day old larval zebrafish can perform multiple sensory motor
 integrating tasks like tracking of prey and predator avoidance.
 In such behaviors, multiple sensory inputs converge on different brain
 areas, these signals are then transformed to infer motion of prey, or predator
 and elicit a behavior to swim towards or away.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To understand the specific roles of neurons in these behavior, we could
 benefit form as many tools as are available to 'break' the circuit apart.
 In this regard, again, the larval zebrafish is ideally suited for circuit
 based neuroscience (refs).
 It offers the convenience of powerful genetic tools, well-stocked mutant
 libraries and more importantly for circuit neuroscience, the transparent
 brain of the larval zebrafish, coupled with genetic calcium based reporters
 and light-sheet microscopy, has allowed unprecedented ability to image
 from the whole brain (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Ahrens:2012ej,Ahrens:2015gv,Friedrich:2010hj"

\end_inset

).
 Although the activity of neurons during such tasks is typically distributed
 over multiple brain areas, it is known to be conserved from animal to animal
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Portugues:2014fn"

\end_inset

).
 Recent advances in high-throughput electron microscopy now allows us to
 integrate detailed anatomical features from physiologically recorded cells
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Briggman:2011ct,Helmstaedter:2013iv,Takemura:2013ea"

\end_inset

).
 In the Drosophila larva, such techniques have allowed for the discovery
 of complex architectures that allow for the convergence of multiple inputs
 from multiple sensory modalities (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Ohyama:2015kb"

\end_inset

