Here we combined functional calcium imaging along with serial-section electron
 microscopy in the larval zebrafish hindbrain.
 We looked at a circuit that is responsible for the stabilization of the
 eye during periods of eye-fixation.
 Spontaneous saccadic eye-movements are typically followed by short periods
 of eye-fixation for a few seconds.
 During these fixations, the motor neurons that innervate the eye muscles,
 receive a tonic input from a subset of neurons in the hindbrain (cite).
 This subset of neurons are responsible for transforming the incoming eye-veloci
ty signals from saccadic neurons, to eye-position signals.
 This transformation, from velocity to position, suggests that these neurons
 are performing temporal integration.
 These cells are therefore referred to as velocity-to-position neural integrator
 cells (VPNI).
 Similar neurons have been shown to exist in the goldfish area1 (cite) and
 in the non-human primate (cite).
 In the goldfish brain stem, eye-position sensitive cells were seen to be
 have similar morphologies, with ipsilaterally projecting cells having large
 dendritic fields with axons that gave rise to collaterals and contralateral
 projecting cells what did not have any ipsilateral projections and smaller
 dendritic fields (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Aksay:2000cn"

\end_inset

).
 The emergence of axonal collaterals on the same side as other position
 sensitive cells, suggests the possibility of local feedback loops that
 might drive this persistent activity.
 Supporting this evidence was also evidence that shows that pairs of neurons
 on the same side have highly correlated activity, both in fish (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Aksay:2003un"

\end_inset

) and in monkeys (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Dale:2015hh"

\end_inset

).
 Neurons that are clustered together, tend to have similar decay times,
 correlate similarly with eye-position and velocity and have high pairwise
 correlations (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Miri:2011ib"

\end_inset

).
 Here we also show that neurons that are clustered together also have similar
 anatomy and axonal projection patterns.
